Sneaky valgrind trick to detect stack memory issues.After something is popped from a stack, we overwrite the memorynwith uninitialised data (if JQ_DEBUG is on). This means thatnvalgrind reports use-after-pop as an uninitialised memory error.n

Let @uri produce uppercase hexadecimal digits...instead of lowercase ones.nnAccording to RFC 3986,nn   The uppercase hexadecimal digits 'A' through 'F' are equivalent ton   the lowercase digits 'a' through 'f', respectively.  If two URIsn   differ only in the case of hexadecimal digits used in percent-encodedn   octets, they are equivalent.  For consistency, URI producers andn   normalizers should use uppercase hexadecimal digits for all percent-n   encodings.nnSee https://github.com/stedolan/jq/issues/451 for details.nnTest suite and manual are also updated to reflect this change.nnSigned-off-by: Nicolas Williams <nico@cryptonector.com>n

Fix off-by-one in TCONow we have the ability to define a generator in jq:nndef for(cond; update):ndef _for:nif cond then ., (update | _for) else . end;n_for;nnfor(. < 10; . + 1) # generates numbers between `.` and 10nnRunning this by hand with --debug-dump-disasm (with a fix for thatncoming up next) we can see that the call to _for is optimized:nn_for:0:n  0000 DUPn  0001 CALL_JQ cond:0^1n  0005 JUMP_F 0022n  0007 POPn  0008 FORK 0012n  0010 JUMP 0020n  0012 CALL_JQ update:1^1n  0016 TAIL_CALL_JQ _for:0^1n  0020 JUMP 0023n  0022 POPn  0023 RETnnAnd timing this with 1000, 10000, 100000 iterations shows thatnindeed we must be applying TCO; otherwise, without TCO, this getsnvery slow very quickly.n

Add Streaming parser (--stream)Streaming means that outputs are produced as soon as possible.  With then`foreach` syntax one can write programs which reduce portions of thenstreaming parse of a large input (reduce into proper JSON values, fornexample), and discard the rest, processing incrementally.nnThis:nn$ jq -c --stream .nnshould produce the same output as this:nn$ jq -c '. as $dot | path(..) as $p | $dot | getpath($p) | [$p,.]'nnThe output of `jq --stream .` should be a sequence of`[[<path>],<leaf>]`nand `[[<path>]]` values.  The latter indicate that the array/object atnthat path ended.nnScalars and empty arrays and objects are leaf values for this purpose.nnFor example, a truncated input produces a path as soon as possible, thennlater the error:nn$ printf '[0,n'|./jq -c --stream .n[[0],0]nparse error: Unfinished JSON term at EOF at line 3, column 0n$n

Allow resetting of jq err callbackThis will be useful for the upcoming test-erroneous-programs improvementnto --run-tests, so we can switch between the default error reportingnmethod (print to stderr) to a method internal to --run-tests, and back.nnThe idea is that when testing programs that are expected to compile (andnlink), it'd be nice if errors continue going to stderr, while whenntesting programs that must fail to compile (or link), the error has tonbe captured so it can be compared to the error expected by the test.n

Add support for testing erroneous programsThis will allow moving tests of some tests from tests/run tontests/all.test.  It will also be useful for more extensive testing ofnlanguage features where we want nice error messages, or errors at all,nto be produced, particularly language features where the errors arise atncompile-, codegen-, or link-time rather than parse-time.nnThis does not check for run-time errors though -- those we can alreadyncheck for with try/catch.nn$ jq --run-testsn%%FAILnbreaknjq: error: break used outside labeled control structuren^Dn1 of 1 tests passed (0 malformed)n$n

exit with non-zero code on runtime exceptionsWith this change, runtime exceptions are propagated to non-zero exitncode of 'jq', allow better scripting and automation. The new exit codenvalue is 5.nnThis allows using the shell's and/or operations ('&&' and '||') tondetect input runtime exceptions.nnBefore:nruntime exceptions are printed to STDERR, but not reported as non-zero exit-code:n$ echo 'hello' | jq '.|tonumber' ; echo $?njq: error: Invalid numeric literal at EOF at line 1, column 5 (while parsing 'hello')n0nnAfter:n$ echo 'hello' | ./jq '.|tonumber' ;  echo $?njq: error: Invalid numeric literal at EOF at line 1, column 5 (while parsing 'hello')n5nnNote that there's a subtle interplay when using -e option.nThe value of the non-zero exit code changes from 4 to 5, but it stillnindicates a 'failure' or non-true value.nnBefore:n$ echo 'hello' | jq -e '.|tonumber' ;  echo $?njq: error: Invalid numeric literal at EOF at line 1, column 5 (while parsing 'hello')n4nnAfter:n$ echo 'hello' | ./jq -e '.|tonumber' ;  echo $?njq: error: Invalid numeric literal at EOF at line 1, column 5 (while parsing 'hello')n5n

Handle NUL in escaped-string outputWhen escaping string (e.g. for `@tsv` or `@csv` outputs),nescape NULs as '0'.nnExisting behaviour, unchanged by this patch:nn$ echo 'au0000b' | ./jq '.'nau0000bn$ echo 'au0000b' | ./jq -r '.' | od -an0000000   a nul   b  nln0000004nnWhen using `@tsv`, escape NUL to `0`:nn$ echo 'au0000b' | ./jq -r '[.]|@tsv'na0bn$ echo 'au0000b' | ./jq '[.]|@tsv'na0bn

Fixes manual generation with psychWhen running `make` I ran into a couple of problems building the manual. WhilenI'm not entirely sure that this is the root cause, it appears to have beennrelated to the fact that ruby 2.0 dropped syck completely in favor of psychn(which was introduced in 1.9.2) for YAML processing. I'm currently using rubyn2.1.0p0.nnI'm assuming that the fact that the YAML engine was explicitly set to syck innthe Rakefile was an attempt to work around some incompatibility between the twonlibraries, so I looked into what would be necessary to get it to work with thennewer one. regex functions: report informative error if not available.When trying to use the new regex functions (match/test/sub/capture/etc)nin a JQ that was compiled without the ONIGURAMA regex library,nreport an informative error message instead of a 'not defined' error.nnBefore:nn$ echo 'foo' | ./jq-old 'test(foo)'njq: error: test/1 is not defined at <top-level>, line 1:ntest(foo)njq: 1 compile errornnAfter:nn$ echo 'foo' | ./jq 'test(foo)'njq: error: jq was compiled without ONIGURAMA regex libary. match/test/sub and related functions are not available.n

--raw-input ought to read NULs (partial fix #760)We can't know how many bytes fgets() read when we reach EOF and fgets()ndidn't see a newline; we can only assume that at least strlen(buf) bytesnwere read.  This is quite obnoxious if one wants to use NULs in rawninput, but at least we can make reading a0b0c0 with no newlinenyield a0b0c, losing only the final sequence of NULs.nnWe can't use getline() either, since it will want to allocate a buffernbig enough for an entire line, and we might not have any newlines in ourninput.  A complete fix will have to use getc() or read(), preferably thenlatter.n

Report filename:line on runtime errors (fix #752)With this patch, jq run-time errors printed to stderr will contain thenfilename and line of the offending input.nnBut note that the JSON text parser does (yet) print the input filenamenon parse error.  A jq run-time error is a jq program error, notnincluding syntax errors nor JSON text input format errors.nnExamples:nnWith stdin and multiple lines:nn$ printf '{a:43}n{a:{b:66}}n' | ./jq '.a+1'n44njq: error (at stdin:2): object and number cannot be addednnWith multiple files:nn$ printf '{a:43}' > 1.jsonn$ printf '{a:hello}n' > 2.jsonn$ printf '{a:{b:66}}n' > 3.jsonn$ ./jq '[.a]|@tsv' 1.json 2.json 3.jsonn43nhellonjq: error (at 3.json:1): object is not valid in a csv rownnWith very long lines (spanning multiple `fgets` calls):nn$ (  printf '{a:43}n' ;n printf '{a:{b:[' ; seq 10000 | paste -d, -s | tr -d 'n' ;n printf ']}}n' ;n printf '{a:hello}n' ) | ./jq '[.a] | @tsv'n43njq: error (at stdin:2): object is not valid in a csv rownhellonnWith raw input:nn$ seq 1000 | ./jq --raw-input 'select(.==700) | . + 10'njq: error (at stdin:700): string and number cannot be addednnCaveat:nThe reported line will be the last line of the (valid) parsed JSON data.nExample:nn$ printf '{na:nhellonnn}n' | ./jq '.a+4'njq: error (at stdin:6): string and number cannot be addedn

Resolve shift/reduce conflict of 'def' vs '|'This was an important conflict. In the following expression:nndef a: 0; . | annBison needs to decide between these two equally validnparses:nn(def a: 0; .) | andef a: 0; (. | a)nnFor jq we want the second one, because the first results inna/0 is not defined. In the current parser the first parsenis a reduce and the second parse is a shift. Since Bisonnprefers to shift in shift/reduce conflicts, we accidentallyngot the correct behavior.nnThis commit adds a precedence level FUNCDEF which is lowernprecedence than '|', meaning we explicitly choose thencorrect parse.nnOf course many unit tests already cover this case, but Inadded one specifically for it.n
Resolve remaining shift/reduce conflicts involving '?'By lowering the precedence of rules that should never usenthe generic Exp '?' rule.n

Make |= delete LHS when RHS is empty (Fix #1314)Now that #1313 is fixed, |= no longer outputs null when the RHS updatenexpression outputs empty.nnWhen a user wants to keep the current value of the LHS they would haventhe RHS update expression output `.`, so having `empty` achieve the samenthing would be redundant.  The obvious thing to do is to delete the LHSnwhen the RHS update outputs `empty` (i.e., doesn't output any values).nnIt's reasonable to think that existing programs won't be broken by thisnchange, because reduce and |= not handling empty well is clearly a bug.n(Though it's possible that some programs were using empty to quicklynterminate reduce or |=, it's not likely.  They should use label/breakninstead.)nnPrior to this change |= would use the _last_ value output by the RHSnupdate expression.  With this change |= will use the _first_ valueninstead.  This change _is_ a minor backwards-incompatible change.  Itnmay or may not be acceptable; we'll see.  It is a useful change in thatnit makes |= faster when the update expression produces multiple values.n

Revert reduce: handle empty updates (fix #1313)This reverts commit e24af3c78e78a3aab05a2800d825d56f1d842b1b.nnWhile the semantics are desirable, there is no way to implement themnefficiently.  The reason is that in order to handle backtracking (empty)nfrom the state update expression, we have to retain a reference to thenreduction state value in order to restore it upon backtracking.nRetaining a reference to the reduction state kills performance byncausing lots of additional memory allocations and garbage because theninput to the update expression will always have at least two references,nthus no changes to it can be done in-place, and all changes end up beingnCoW changes.nnAvoiding this is the very reason for the LOADVN instruction (leavingn`null` in the variable loaded from).n

Bugfix: Math function checkingWe had config machinery that determined which math functions arenavailable in libc. If a c math function was missing on the host system,nthen the corresponding jq function would be removed from the source,nenabling the build to proceed anyway. The detection machinery was brokennin a subtle way, as was shown after glibc updated to 2.27, dropping then`pow10` function. This caused compilation to fail.nnThe essential problem was that we detected whether a math function wasnavailable by compiling and linking a small program evaluating thatnfunction on constants. However, since gcc's optimization machinery hasnspecial knowledge of some math functions (e.g. `pow10`), it cannoptimize them away, even if they don't exist in the library and are notnlinkable. That is, the following example compiles and links againstnglibc 2.27, even though `pow10` has been removed:n```nint main () {n  printf(%f, pow10(0.5));n  return 0;n}n```nnWhat?!nOn the other hand, this program does not link:n```nnint main () {n  double f;n  printf(%f, &f);n  printf(%f, pow10(f));n  return 0;n}n```nnIn the first program the call to `pow10` can be optimized away as anconstant expression. This requires GCC to know about `pow10` (which itndoes!), but it does not require `pow10` to be in the library (andnactually linkable).nnThe solution is to use autoconf's machinery for detecting functionnpresence, instead of our own (buggy) machinery. This has the addednbenefit of simplifying the code.nnThe bug was reported in issue #1659n

Fix assert in generator subexpressions (fix #1875)Expressions of the form `path(EXPR) | select(GENERATOR)`, where `EXPR`nis a path expression and `GENERATOR` is a generator conditionalnexpression (e.g., `has(a), has(b)`) cause an assertion if thenjq_state VM is torn down too soon. docs: fix seriously dangerous download instructions for Arch LinuxThe current instructions tell users to perform two actions:n- update the package databasen- install the jq packagennThe only thing users need to or should be doing is actually installingnthe jq package -- regardless of which version is being installed.nGuidelines on how to perform system updates are massively out of scope.nnIn the case of partially performing a system update as a prerequisitenfor installing jq, the official guidance from Arch Linux is not to donthis: partial updates are not supported, we refuse to support them, andnanyone who does try to perform them anyway is assumed to know so muchnabout their system that they clearly do not ever need help from anyonenelse (which is a good thing since they won't get it). The result is anfrankensteined system that can only ever be supported by the person whonfrankensteined it to begin with. The only reason the package managerneven allows it to occur in the first place is because otherndistributions using pacman might have different LTS policies, andnbecause it would prevent expert users from being in control of theirnsystem, as per the traditional Unix philosophy:nnUnix was not designed to stop you from doing stupid things, becausenthat would also stop you from doing clever things.nnConsequences of performing partial updates without understanding thenramifications in extensive detail can include breaking the partiallynupdated application (jq), breaking any application that shares a mutualndependency with the partially updated application (which jq is *lucky*nto only depend on the ever-backwards-compatible glibc), or breaking thenentire operating system by leaving armed traps behind for the next timena `pacman -S new-package` is executed and thereby breaks *its* cascadingndependencies.nnSee:nhttps://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/System_maintenance#Partial_upgrades_are_unsupportedn
